column1: Between 21 November 2017 and 30 September 2018, how will S&P next adjust the United Kingdom's long-term issuer credit rating?
column6: ['Finance', 'Economic Indicators']
column11: Revisions to the "outlook" will not suffice. S&P and Fitch downgraded the United Kingdom after the 2016 Brexit vote, and Moody's did the same in September 2017. While S&P recently reaffirmed its AA rating, it cautioned that the risk of a disorderly Brexit may lead to a further downgrade (Reuters, Financial Times). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

The UK's economic figures are likely to be confusing or unusual in the coming few months. I expect that the credit rating people and the UK authorities will be aware that the figures may not be reflecting what similar figures would normally signal. For example I am hearing that businesses are finding sales are weak, but at the same time are raising output sharply. I only have access to information supplied by friends (so not reported in the media, not from surveys). I am not saying that the businesses with weakening sales are necessarily the same businesses that are increasing production. The increased production is taking place to build up stocks in case of a hard Brexit. I have heard 2 months extra stock as being a target (to be held in the UK or in the rest of the EU depending on the nature of the products). The exact reason for the falling sales is less clear, but uncertainty is the likely reason. The consequences are that UK GDP could appear to be higher in the short term, but because this if the concerns about disrupted trade are resolved, presumably stocks could be reduced again which would depress GDP in the medium term. If the need to hold more stocks becomes permanent that will require firms to use more capital (equity or borrowing) which has a cost and prices will reflect that. It can be noted that a lower value for the pound has not proved to be a great boost to exports. That is not really surprising because in order to boost exports investment is likely to be needed (some production for domestic consumption could be switched to export, but increased exporting is likely to involve investing in marketing, distributions, variations in design as well as requiting and training labour, installing or upgrading plant and machinery etc.) In a period of great uncertainty many businesses will hold back investments or direct investment money into countries less likely to suffer from the uncertainty. So I expect contradictory signals on the state of the UK economy between now and 30 Sept.

In 2013, Moody’s cut the UK’s credit rating from Aaa to Aa1. After the Brexit vote, in June 2016 S&P cut the UK’s rating from AAA to AA (2 notches), Fitch cut from AA+ to AA, and Moody’s cut the outlook to negative. In September 2017, Moody’s downgraded from Aa1 to Aa2 with a stable outlook, stating that Brexit was creating economic uncertainty, exacerbating the UK’s poor progress on debt reduction. Moody’s explained that the UK was increasing spending on health and social care, among other areas. In October 2017, S&P and Fitch both reaffirmed their AA ratings, both with a negative outlook.

Regarding the Brexit risk; Macron's visit to the UK and his interview with Andrew Marr has (again) confirmed the likely Brexit outcome. Or at least the probable options. The media have added some spin to what Macron said which can be ignored. The two options on offer to the UK will be (a) a free trade deal excluding services (specifically financial services) similar to Canada (b) a deal similar to Norway that could include financial services and could include being in the Customs Union. The problem with (a) is that it does not offer any answer to how the agreement that the border between the UK and Ireland will have no controls (in practice introducing 3rd country controls on most UK borders with the EU would be a massive problem and cost), and it does not help the UK's need for full access to the EU Single Market. Polls are indicating that most voters want the UK to remain in the Single Market and Customs Union. So this (the "Canada" option seems less likely to be chosen by the UK)

There could be be fallout from the Carillion liquidation. PFI contracts were seen as a way of keeping public debts off the UK's books, so that capital expenditure on public sector projects could be converted into operating expenditure and not show as part of the UK National Debt. The collapse of Carillian (will/might?) expose that ultimately the UK state would face liabilities when a PFI contractor fails. There have been questions asked as to how big the total PFI debts are; the UK Government does not seem to have the figures. It is part of the nature of financial scares that some seemingly small, contained event, prompts markets to take another look at wider cases and then realise that what had appeared to be an isolated failure is more systemic than had been accounted for. If in looking at Carillion markets notice that there are lots of "safe" PFI companies (and other types of companies) that have huge levels of borrowing and that when companies that rely of chains of subcontractors to do their work go bust then that ripples through the construction chain (subcontractors who were owned money might also go bust, material suppliers might go bust.) Maybe the Carillion failure can be contained but there is a risk that it could be a much bigger problem than it appears, and if it pushes up UK National Debt it could trigger a revision to the UK credit rating. It could also in the longer term mean that there are calls for businesses to be more financed by equity rather than debt,
